symbolic significance tht would restore his/her dignity and mark an
acknowledgment on the part of the wrongdoer, it is not the wrongdoer's task to
point out the practical futility of apologies and "refuse to apologize" on the
grounds that it is not in the interest of the wronged.  that phenomenon, of the
power-majority deciding what is in the best interest of the subordinated,
perpetuates an unjust hierarchy where those in power don't think they have to
listen.--maria damon
