Date:         Mon, 24 Apr 1995 19:27:51 -0400
Reply-To:     UB Poetics discussion group <POETICS@UBVM.CC.BUFFALO.EDU>
Sender:       UB Poetics discussion group <POETICS@UBVM.CC.BUFFALO.EDU>
From:         Tom Mandel <tmandel@UMD5.UMD.EDU>
Subject:      Re: re-politics again
 
Ed, I think we'll have to disagree about Bakhtin, and maybe about
the meaning of the term "theology" too, since I don't see Jung,
who I certainly would classify as pernicious, in that light whatever.
 
But I'm interested in what you mean by the phrase "seeing movement
in the work as in the experience as namable rather than merely
manifest."
 
Without anticipating your response to that interest -- I mean it as
a query -- I would just say that "manifest" as you use the term
is to me a theological term, if a term of Greek theology and
perhaps also gnosticism rather than of Xtian theology.
 
To "manifest" I would not oppose "namable" but rather
speak-able, subject to commentary, to response, to something
further. Reading, again to me, is this "further" or "other"
and it makes and remakes the poem which is not an object
(again, to me) but a subject, a speaking being.
 
 
Tom Mandel
