        I never liked Cordelia all that much in Lear,  Will never painted
her fully in my mind and he wimped out at the end by having her die.  I
know she's commonly considered the" redeemer", but in that sense she
loses her feminine aspect.  Her character and actions are masculine, just
as Goneril and Regan.
        A piece I've always liked but puzzled over was Tennyson's The
Princess, inparticular " The Woman's cause is the Man's"
 
                For Woman is not undeveloped man,
                But diverse: could we make as the man,
                Sweet Love were slain: his dearest bond is this,
                Not like to like, but like in difference.
 
 
 
 
 
                        Lindz
